    "content": "**YES** — solid approach, with one small caveat.\n\nThe introduce-then-shorten pattern is standard academic practice. Reader gets the full conceptual payload once, the TN anchors it, and \"character\" carries the weight in running text.\n\n**Caveat:** \"Character\" alone is ambiguous in English (moral character, fictional character, written character). This works as long as:\n- The introductory passage makes the specific meaning unmistakable\n- Surrounding context in each subsequent use keeps it clear\n- At significant topic shifts (new chapter/section), a brief re-anchoring like \"character (德)\" appears once to re-orient the reader\n\nOtherwise, clean solution. Approve."
